Explainability Module

Epistemic governance layer.
Role-scoped truth projection.
Redaction boundary between domain reality and observable reality.

This module does not control authorization.

It controls what truth is allowed to be seen.

Core Principle

Not all truths are observable.
Observability is role-scoped.
Redaction must be deterministic and structural.

This is not RBAC.

This is epistemic control.

Domain Responsibility

This module owns:

Explainability roles (epistemic tiers)

Redaction policies (structural visibility)

Decision redaction

Ledger commit redaction

Routing decision redaction

Counterfactual visibility control

Disbursement explainability redaction

It does not:

Authorize requests

Fetch from database

Serialize dates

Transform Prisma entities

Infer lifecycle

Mutate data

It transforms read models into observable truth.

Epistemic Roles (Not Auth Roles)
type ExplainabilityRole =
| "INTERNAL"
| "AUDITOR"
| "PARTNER"
| "PUBLIC";

These define who may observe which dimensions of truth.

They are not permission roles.

They define epistemic scope.

An INTERNAL actor sees everything.
A PUBLIC actor sees narrative-level summaries.

This separation protects:

Privacy

Governance integrity

Legal defensibility

Operational clarity

Policy Engine

EXPLAINABILITY_POLICY

Centralized, declarative visibility matrix.

Each role defines visibility over:

Decision fields

Ledger fields

Routing fields

Counterfactuals

No scattered if (role === …) logic.

All redaction derives from policy.

This prevents:

Drift between modules

Accidental visibility expansion

Shadow access rules

Redaction Architecture

Redaction operates on read-model DTOs only.

Never Prisma entities.

Never DB models.

Why?

Because explainability must be decoupled from persistence.

If your schema changes,
explainability policy must not collapse.

Decision Redaction

redactDecision()

Controls visibility of:

actorUserId

intentContext

reason

Authoritative and temporal metadata always preserved.

Reason may remain visible even when actor identity is hidden.

This allows:

Governance transparency

Identity protection

Context-limited review

Ledger Redaction

redactLedgerCommit()

Ledger is immutable truth.

But not all fields are globally observable.

Visibility gates:

actorUserId

intentContext

payload

authorityProof

signature

Commitment hash and supersession always remain visible.

Why?

Because audit integrity must remain reconstructible
even if contextual metadata is hidden.

Routing Redaction

redactRoutingDecision()

Routing outcome remains visible.

Identity of decider may not.

Counterfactual visibility is explicitly gated.

Counterfactuals are powerful.

They reveal policy reasoning.

That is not always externally visible.

Counterfactual Control

Two functions:

allowCounterfactuals()

redactCounterfactual()

Counterfactuals must be explicitly allowed.

If not allowed → return undefined.

Never partially redact.

Binary exposure prevents inference leakage.

Disbursement Explainability

redactDisbursementExplanation()

Domain-level redaction.

Important:

Dates remain Date objects.
No transport conversion.
No serialization.

Role tiers:

INTERNAL / AUDITOR
→ Full visibility

PARTNER
→ Hide payee, authority, failure

PUBLIC
→ Only structural summary

PUBLIC must see:

status

summary

amount

timeline

narrative explainability

But never:

payee identity

authority proof

failure internals

Financial systems require tiered transparency.

Separation of Layers

This module sits between:

Loader → Domain DTO → Redaction → Mapper → Transport DTO

Redaction must:

Not mutate

Not serialize

Not depend on Prisma

Not introduce transport formatting

Serialization belongs in mapper.
Authorization belongs in middleware.
Explainability belongs here.

Invariants

Redaction must be pure.

Redaction must not mutate input.

Policy must be centralized.

Redaction must never import Prisma.

Ledger structural integrity must remain reconstructible.

Counterfactual visibility must be explicit.

Dates must not be stringified here.

Break these and explainability becomes inconsistent.

Failure Modes Considered

Schema evolution
→ Redaction unaffected (DTO-level only)

Policy expansion
→ Single-file update

New role added
→ Compiler forces policy mapping

Prisma field change
→ No coupling to persistence

Accidental identity leak
→ Prevented via centralized policy

Scalability Characteristics

Current complexity:

O(n) over read-model arrays

Zero database operations

Pure structural mapping

Future safe expansions:

Add new explainability tier

Add new visibility dimensions

Add per-field masking logic

Introduce structured visibility analytics

Redaction remains cheap and deterministic.

Why Redaction Is Structural (Not Conditional Strings)

Because removing fields entirely:

Prevents partial inference

Simplifies API contracts

Avoids “empty but present” leakage

Keeps observability binary and explicit

Undefined fields are safer than null placeholders.

Observability Philosophy

Internal sees causality.
Auditor sees reasoning without identity.
Partner sees operational outcome.
Public sees narrative truth.

Explainability is not data dumping.

It is controlled epistemology.

Mental Model

The ledger contains objective history.

The database contains projections.

The explainability layer determines:

Which version of truth a given observer is allowed to perceive.

It is a constitutional filter between fact and perception.

If auditors replay your ledger,
they should see the same causality INTERNAL sees.

If the public reads your API,
they should see narrative integrity without operational leakage.

That is the balance this module enforces.
